Thanks for the report! The root cause is that `'\ud83d'` is an isolated UTF-16 **high surrogate** — it is not a valid Unicode scalar value on its own. When passed to the native `sk_fontmgr_match_family_style_character` function, CoreText on iOS does not handle the invalid codepoint gracefully and hangs.

As a **caller-side workaround** until this is fixed in the library, combine the surrogate pair into a valid codepoint before calling `MatchCharacter`:

```csharp
// If your string contains a surrogate pair:
var codePoint = char.IsHighSurrogate(text[0])
    ? char.ConvertToUtf32(text[0], text[1])
    : text[0];
var typeface = SKFontManager.Default.MatchCharacter(codePoint);
```

The long-term fix is to add surrogate validation inside `MatchCharacter` so the wrapper throws `ArgumentOutOfRangeException` instead of passing an invalid codepoint to native code.
